{{Infobox building | name = 52 Broadway | image = ExchangeCourtBuildingNYC1920.jpg | image_caption = The building in 1920 | former_names = Exchange Court Building, Chemical Bank Building | building_type = Office | architectural_style = | address = 52-56 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] | location_city = [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] | location_country = [[United States]] | coordinates = {{coord|40|42|23|N|74|0|44|W|format=dms}} | completion_date = 1898 | renovation_date = 1982 | height = {{convert|221.51|ft|m}} | floor_count = 20 | architecture_firm = [[Clinton and Russell]] | ren_firm = [[Emery Roth & Sons]] | references = <ref name=Emporis>{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/building/52broadway-newyorkcity-ny-usa|title=52 Broadway|publisher=Emporis|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> }} '''52 Broadway''', formerly known as the '''Exchange Court Building''' or '''Chemical Bank Building''' is a high-rise building on [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] and Exchange Place in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. The building was originally built with 12 floors in 1898 by Clinton & Russell, architects, but it was rebuilt and restored in 1980-1982 by [[Emery Roth|Emery Roth & Sons]]. It is now {{convert|67.52|m}} high with 20 floors.<ref name=Emporis />
==Tenants== In September 1903, the [[Consolidated National Bank]] took out a five-year lease on around 2,500 square feet of ground floor at the Exchange Court Building, which was located at the corner of [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] and [[Exchange Place (Manhattan)|Exchange Place]].<ref name=nyt-quarters>{{Citation | date = September 2, 1903 | title = Consolidated National's New Quarters. | publisher =''[[The New York Times]]'' | publication-place =New York | page = 11 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1903/09/02/archives/consolidated-nationals-new-quarters-time-extended-for-hooley.html | accessdate =January 21, 2017 }}</ref>
The naval architectural firm [[Gielow & Orr]] had their headquarters in the building in the early 20th century.<ref>{{cite book|title=MotorBoating|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0BaE537n_ggC&pg=PA53|date=September 1919|page=53|issn=1531-2623}}</ref> The [[United Federation of Teachers]] currently has its headquarters in the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uft.org/contact|title=Contact|publisher=United Federation of Teachers|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref>
