'''Þorsteinn Baldur Friðriksson'''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kjarninn.is/frettir/2016-08-31-plain-vanilla-lokad-islandi-ollum-starfsmonnum-sagt-upp/ |title=Plain Vanilla lokað á Íslandi – öllum starfsmönnum sagt upp |first=Þórunn Elísabet |last=Bogadóttir |date=August 31, 2016 |website=[[Kjarninn]] |accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref> (born 1979), commonly anglicised as '''Thor Fridriksson''', is an Icelandic businessman. He was the founder and [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of [[Plain Vanilla Games]], a [[Reykjavík]]-based [[video game developer]], until its defunction in August 2016.<ref name="WSJ">{{cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2013/12/26/quizup-takes-over-where-trivial-pursuit-left-off-the-mobile-generation/ |title=QuizUp Takes Over Where Trivial Pursuit Left Off — The Mobile Generation |first=Lora |last=Kolodny |date=27 December 2013 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Þorsteinn is a native [[Icelanders|Icelander]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fortune.com/2014/03/06/how-hit-trivia-app-quizup-survived-the-hype-cycle/ |title=How hit trivia app QuizUp survived the hype cycle |first=Erin |last=Griffith |date=6 March 2014 |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref> He received a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree from the [[University of Oxford]] in 2009.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}

== Career ==
Þorsteinn was working with the broadband-ISP startup Hive until it was purchased by Vodafone in 2007.<ref name="FastCompany">{{cite web |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3027109/how-the-creator-of-quizup-turned-a-string-of-foolish-moves-into-a-10-million-user-app |title=How The Creator Of QuizUp Turned A String Of Foolish Moves Into A 10 Million-User App |first=David |last=Lumb |date=28 February 2014 |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |accessdate=June 24, 2018}}</ref> Deciding to explore a different industry, Þorsteinn became a local TV news reporter.<ref name="WSJ" /><ref name="FastCompany" /> After studying at the University of Oxford, Þorsteinn started Plain Vanilla Games in [[Reykjavík]] during the [[2008–11 Icelandic financial crisis|Icelandic financial crisis]].<ref name="SeattleTimes">{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/startuprsquos-success-with-quizup-app-a-bright-spot-for-icelandrsquos-economy/ |title=Startup's success with QuizUp app a bright spot for Iceland’s economy |first=Jenna |last=Gottlieb |date=6 March 2014 |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref> Þorsteinn and his team at Plain Vanilla Games spent over a year developing an educational app for children called ''The Moogies'',<ref name="FastCompany" /> that failed to gain popularity on the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/katieroof/2014/03/06/quizup-debuts-on-android-how-an-icelandic-game-became-an-overnight-success/ |title=QuizUp Debuts On Android; How An Icelandic Game Became An Overnight Success |first=Katie |last=Roof |date=6 March 2014 |website=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref> Despite the country's economic issues, Þorsteinn decided to keep the Plain Vanilla Games' headquarters located in Reykjavík to help support job growth and other start-up companies.<ref name="SeattleTimes" />

